For a real distinction, we need to be able to conceive of the one thing apart from the\par
other, and vice versa. This one without anything related to the other one, that one without\par
anything related to the first one.\par
   - we need to have a "complete idea" of the one thing apart from the other\par
\par
What better way to show a real distinction???\par
\par
\ul Arnauld's big objection:\ulnone\par
Right triangle example: it's possible to have a clear/distinct idea of a right triangle w/o\par
any understanding of the fact that a\'b2+b\'b2 = c\'b2, and yet the two are in fact inseparable,\par
in fact it's impossible for a right triangle not to have that property.\par
   - So maybe if we had a more complete/adequate understanding of the mind, we would\par
     see that it is physical or it has physical properties that belong to its essence, etc.\par
   - You need to show that you/we have a complete enough idea of the mind to conclude\par
      that nothing physical belongs to its essence.\par
\par
\ul Descartes' reply:\ulnone\par
   - I/we do have a complete idea of the mind, not in the sense that we know everything\par
     there is to know about the mind (adequate idea), but in the sense that what we \i do\par
    \i0  know about it is enough to guarantee it can exist on its own as a substance.\par
  - Same for the body.\par
\par
