\ul Arnauld's objection:\ulnone\par
\pard\li360\sl240\slmult1 Just because you can \b\i clearly conceive \b0\i0 of X without Y, that doesn't mean it's \b\i really possible \b0\i0 to have X without Y.\par
                                         [have a c/d idea]  \par
\cf1\fs4 .\cf0\fs36\par
   - I can have a \i c/d idea\i0  of a right triangle without having any idea of the Pyth. thm.,\par
     but that doesn't mean it's \i really possible\i0  to have a right triangle that doesn't obey the Pyth.\fs8  \fs36 thm.\par
\cf1\fs4 .\cf0\fs36\par
   - I can have a \i c/d idea\i0  of a mind without having any idea of anything physical,\par
     but that doesn't mean it's \i really possible \i0 to have a mind that has nothing physical to it.\par
\cf1\fs4 .\cf0\fs36\par
   - These days people worry about whether/when "conceivability entails possibility".\par
\pard\sl240\slmult1\cf1\fs30 .\cf0\fs36\par
\ul Descartes' response:\ulnone\par
\pard\li360\sl240\slmult1 Substance:\par
   - It's not just a matter of clearly conceiving of X without Y, it's also a matter of\par
     clearly conceiving of X \b\i as a complete thing\b0\i0  [i.e., as a substance] without Y.\par
\cf1\fs4 .\cf0\fs36\par
   - And also vice versa: clearly conceiving of Y as a complete thing without X.\par
\cf1\fs4 .\cf0\fs36\par
Active exclusion:\par
   - It's not just a matter of clearly conceiving of X \b\i without conceiving of Y\b0\i0 , it's also a matter of\par
      clearly conceiving of X \b\i while actively excluding Y\b0\i0 .\par
\cf1\fs4 .\cf0\fs36\par
   - Indeed, while excluding anything \b\i Y-related or Y-ish\b0\i0 .\par
\cf1\fs4 .\cf0\fs36\par
The inflated first premise:\par
  - I can have a c/d idea of the mind as a complete thinking thing/substance while actively\fs12  \fs36 excluding\par
    anything physical (And vice versa: I can have a c/d idea of the body as a complete extended\par
    thing/substance while actively excluding anything thought-related from it.)\par
\cf1\fs4 .\cf0\fs36\par
         My remark:\par
            - Now the first premise has been so inflated that it's not clear whether to accept it.\par
\cf1\fs4 .\cf0\fs36\par
            - I might be willing to sign on to a mere c/d idea of thinking going on without any idea of \par
              anything physical.\par
\cf1\fs4 .\cf0\fs36\par
            - But I'm not sure whether I have a c/d idea of a full-fledged thinking substance while \par
              actively excluding anything physical.\par
